President Cyril Ramaphosa has appointed Justice Mandisa Maya as Deputy Chief Justice of Mzansi. She is the first woman to hold this position. The announcement of the appointment, which is in accordance with Section 174(3) of the Constitution of the Republic of South Africa, was made on Monday, 25 July. Maya, who is currently the president of the Supreme Court of Appeal, will start her new position on 1 September. ALSO READ: Hijacking claims officer’s life! Ramaphosa said Maya brings more than two decades of a distinguished career as a judicial officer. “Justice Maya will contribute to the ongoing transformation process of the judiciary. Her ascendency to the apex court will serve as a beacon of hope for scores of young women and make them believe that South Africa is a country of possibilities, regardless of gender, social or economic circumstances,” said the president. Maya replaces Justice Raymond Zondo who was appointed as Chief Justice in March following the retirement of former Chief Justice Mogoeng Mogoeng.